The direction vector of the line of intersection is orthogonal to the normal vectors of both planes, namely $\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -6 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix}.$  Hence, the direction vector of the line of intersection is
\[\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \times \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -6 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ -12 \\ -12 \end{pmatrix} = -12 \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.\]Thus, the direction vector of the line of intersection is $\begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.$  Hence, the equation of the line of intersection is of the form
\[\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 8 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} + t \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 1 \\ 1 \end{pmatrix}.\]Let $Q = (2,2,0)$ be the projection of $P = (8,0,0)$ onto the plane $2x - 6y + 6z = 2.$  Then
\[\overrightarrow{PQ} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} - \begin{pmatrix} 8 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -6 \\ 2 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}.\]Hence, the distance between the planes is
\[\frac{|-6|}{\sqrt{2}} = \boxed{3 \sqrt{2}}.\]

