Let $\mathbf{v}$ be the vector pointing from $(0,0,0)$ to a point on the second plane, and let $\mathbf{n}_1$ be the normal vector of the first plane.  Let $\mathbf{p}$ be the projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto $\mathbf{n}_1,$ and let $\mathbf{q}$ be the projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto the first plane.  Then $\mathbf{v} = \mathbf{p} + \mathbf{q},$ so $\mathbf{p}$ is the projection of $\mathbf{v}$ onto the first plane.

Since $\mathbf{p}$ is a scalar multiple of $\mathbf{n}_1,$ we can write
\[\mathbf{p} = \operatorname{proj}_{\mathbf{n}_1} \mathbf{v} = \frac{\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}_1}{\|\mathbf{n}_1\|^2} \mathbf{n}_1.\]We have that $\mathbf{v} = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -6 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix}.$  Also,
\[\|\mathbf{n}_1\| = \left\| \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} \right\| = \sqrt{19}.\]Finally,
\[\mathbf{v} \cdot \mathbf{n}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ -6 \\ 6 \end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} = -2.\]Hence,
\[\mathbf{p} = \frac{-2}{19} \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -3 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} -2/19 \\ 6/19 \\ -6/19 \end{pmatrix}.\]The distance between the planes is then given by
\[\frac{|\mathbf{p} \cdot \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}|}{\|\mathbf{n}_1\|} = \boxed{\frac{2}{\sqrt{19}}}.\]

